    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What are roadside attractions?</h3>
            <p>Roadside attractions are unique, quirky, and often unusual landmarks, structures, or displays found alongside highways and roads across America. They range from giant statues and oddly-shaped buildings to folk art installations and peculiar museums, representing local culture, individual creativity, and America's love for the extraordinary.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How do I find roadside attractions for my road trip?</h3>
            <p>Our interactive map is the best way to discover attractions along your route! You can also filter by state or category to find specific types of attractions. Other helpful resources include apps like Roadtrippers and websites like RoadsideAmerica.com that specialize in cataloging these unique stops.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are roadside attractions typically free to visit?</h3>
            <p>Many roadside attractions are free to view from the outside, especially outdoor sculptures, unusual buildings, and photo opportunities. Some larger attractions, museums, or those with indoor components may charge a small admission fee. We recommend checking ahead or looking at the attraction details on our site for specific information.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How much time should I allow for visiting roadside attractions?</h3>
            <p>This varies widely depending on the attraction. Some roadside photo opportunities might only take 10-15 minutes to visit, while larger attractions with museums or activities could require 1-2 hours. We recommend building flexibility into your road trip schedule to accommodate unexpected discoveries!</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What are some of the most famous roadside attractions in America?</h3>
            <p>Some iconic American roadside attractions include Cadillac Ranch in Texas, Wall Drug in South Dakota, Carhenge in Nebraska, the World's Largest Ball of Twine in Kansas, Salvation Mountain in California, and the Giant Blue Whale in Oklahoma. Many of these have become cultural landmarks that represent classic Americana.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are roadside attractions family-friendly?</h3>
            <p>Most roadside attractions are designed to be family-friendly and appeal to visitors of all ages. They often provide unique photo opportunities and memorable experiences for children. Our website includes information about each attraction to help you determine if it's appropriate for your family.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How can I plan a road trip around roadside attractions?</h3>
            <p>Start by selecting a general route or region, then use our map to discover attractions along the way. Consider planning your overnight stops near clusters of attractions, and be flexible with your schedule to allow for unexpected discoveries. Don't plan too many driving hours per day so you have time to enjoy the quirky stops along your journey.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What's the best way to document my visits to roadside attractions?</h3>
            <p>Photos are the most popular way to document visits! Many attractions are designed specifically as photo opportunities. Consider keeping a road trip journal, collecting postcards or small souvenirs, or creating a scrapbook of your visits. You can also share your experiences on social media using hashtags like #RoadsideAttractions or #RoadTripUSA.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Why do roadside attractions exist?</h3>
            <p>Roadside attractions emerged for various reasons: to draw travelers to local businesses, as expressions of folk art or personal passion, as marketing stunts, or to celebrate local history or culture. Many were created during the golden age of American highway travel (1930s-1960s) when businesses competed for the attention of automobile travelers.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are roadside attractions worth the detour?</h3>
            <p>Absolutely! Roadside attractions add character to any road trip and offer unique experiences you won't find anywhere else. They provide perfect break opportunities during long drives, create memorable stories, and allow you to experience the cultural fabric of different regions across America.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
